</section>

<section class="next-steps">
  <h2>What to Do in the Next 30 Days</h2>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Get a Louisiana Citizens quote through a licensed agent.</strong> You cannot apply directly. Ask for the wind/hail deductible expressed as a dollar amount, not just a percentage, so you know your real out-of-pocket exposure before a storm.</li>
    <li><strong>Quote the surplus lines market in parallel.</strong> Because Citizens is priced above market by design, a financially strong non-admitted carrier may be cheaper or offer broader terms. Verify any surplus lines carrier's AM Best or Demotech rating before binding.</li>
    <li><strong>Buy flood coverage separately.</strong> Citizens excludes flood, and in Louisiana flood is frequently the larger loss in a hurricane. Get an NFIP or private flood quote alongside your homeowners coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>If you receive a depopulation/takeout notice, do not let it auto-process.</strong> Check the assuming carrier's financial strength rating and confirm the new policy matches your coverage and deductibles. You have a limited window to decline.</li>
    <li><strong>Look into the Louisiana Fortify Homes Program and FORTIFIED discounts.</strong> A grant-funded FORTIFIED roof can lower your premium through the state's mandated discount and may help you qualify for a private carrier — a path off Citizens. Check the application window at ldi.la.gov.</li>
  </ol>
</section>

